<% include ./partials/header %>

<div>
    <div>
        <p style="font-size: 300%; color: grey">Austin, TX</p>
        <p style="font-size: 200%; color: grey"><%=weather_info.what_day%> <%=weather_info.forecast_date%>, <%=weather_info.weather%></p>
    </div>
    
    <p style="margin-left: -0.3em">
        <img src="/picture/<%=weather_info.weather_icon%>.png" alt="clear!">
        <span style="font-size: 300%;"><%=weather_info.max_temperature%></span>
        <span style="font-size: 210%;"><sup>°F</sup></span>
        <span style="font-size: 150%;">/ <%=weather_info.min_temperature%></span>
        <span style="font-size: 105%;"><sup>°F</sup></span>
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 80%; color: grey"> - Weather predicted at 23:01 <%=weather_info.updated_date%></p>

    <p>Real time weather for comparison: <a href="https://darksky.net/forecast/30.2711,-97.7437/us12/en">Dark Sky</a></p>
    <br>
    <br>
    <p style="font-size: 100%">
        AI-Weather provides weather forecast for Austin using a neural network model (machine learning). <br>
        The training data for the model are collected from Austin and its surrouding cities.</p>
    <p>
        <img class="img-responsive thumbnail" width="800" src="/picture/fiveCity.png" alt="five cities">
    </p>
   
	<br>
	<p style="font-size: 130%"><b>Prediction accuracy</b></p>
	<ul style="font-size: 100%">
		<li >Mean of difference between predicted max temperature and actual max temperature is 3.5°F (1.9°C)</li>
		<li >Mean of difference between predicted max temperature and actual max temperature is 2.9°F (1.6°C)</li>
		<li >Weather (clear, cloud, rain, etc.) prediction accuracy is 65%</li>
	</ul>
    <p>
        <img class="img-responsive thumbnail" width="800" src="/picture/performance.png" alt="performance">
    </p>
	<br>
	<p style="font-size: 130%"><b>Compared with other professional weather webs</b></p>
	    <p>Below is quoted from a <a href="https://www.e-education.psu.edu/meteo3/node/2285">PennState College article</a>:</p>
	    <p>"Temperature forecasts ... have absolute errors of 3 degrees Fahrenheit or less ... a couple of days into the future"</p>
	    
	    <p>Below are quoted from an <a href="https://theoutline.com/post/3826/crap-weather-apps-meteorolgists?zd=1&zi=3pfkmqes">an online publication</a>:</p>
	    <p>"...for one to three day forecasts...The Weather Channel, and Accuweather, which are accurate about 75 percent of the time..."</p>
	    <p>"...Dark Sky and World Weather Online are accurate 64 to 67 percent of the time..."</p>

</div>
